# RATE LIMITER – COMPACT DESIGN (YOUR VERSION)

# 1) CONFIG STORAGE (NOT IN REDIS)
# --------------------------------
# Permanent per-user/per-service rules live in the Rule DB.
# Cache (write-back) sits in front of the DB to avoid DB hits.

# Example rule stored in DB:
{
  "userId": "user123",
  "maxTokens": 100,
  "refillRate": 10,            # tokens per second
  "windowMs": 20000,           # for TTL or fixed window
  "globalLimit": 5000          # optional server-level limit
}

# Rate limiter fetches from cache → if miss → fetch DB → write back.


# 2) REDIS — RUNTIME TOKEN STATE
# -------------------------------
# Only fast-path counters are stored in Redis.

# Key format:
rate_limit:<user|ip|service>

# Value stored in Redis (hash/map-like):
{
  tokens: <float>,             # remaining tokens
  lastRefillTs: <epoch_ms>,    # last update timestamp
  ttl: <window_ms>             # used for auto-expire cleanup
}

# You store:
# - user-level token buckets
# - IP-level token buckets
# - service/global token buckets


# 3) REQUEST FLOW
# ----------------
Actor → Rate Limiter
    → load config from cache (or DB if miss)
    → load token bucket from Redis
    → apply token-bucket math
    → if tokens >= 1 → update Redis + ALLOW
    → else → REJECT 429
→ forward allowed requests to API Gateway / service


# 4) TOKEN BUCKET LOGIC (ATOMIC LUA SCRIPT)
# -----------------------------------------
state = redis.get(key)

elapsed = now - state.lastRefillTs
refill = elapsed * refillRate

newTokens = min(maxTokens, state.tokens + refill)

if newTokens < 1:
    reject
else:
    newTokens -= 1
    update redis { tokens=newTokens, lastRefillTs=now, ttl=windowMs }
    allow


# 5) CLEANUP STRATEGY
# ---------------------
# No manual cleanup.
# Redis TTL handles it automatically.

# When no requests come for a user/service:
# - token bucket key expires after ttl window
# - Redis deletes it
# - No memory leak


# 6) FIXED WINDOW (OPTIONAL SIMPLE MODE)
# ---------------------------------------
count = redis.incr(key)
redis.expire(key, windowMs)
if count > limit → reject
else → allow



